context: In the run-up to the London 2012 Summer Olympic Games and London <b4_0>2012<b4_0/> Summer Paralympic Games, Eton's purpose-built Dorney Lake, a permanent, eight-lane, 2,200 metre course (about 1.4 miles) in a <b6_0>400-acre<b6_0/> park, officially known throughout the Games as Eton Dorney, provided <a0_0>training facilities<a0_0/> for Olympic and Paralympic competitors, and during the Games, hosted the Olympic and Paralympic Rowing competitions as well as the Olympic Canoe Sprint event, attracting over <a1_0><b5_0><b7_0>400,000<b7_0/><b5_0/> visitors during the Games period (around <b8_0>30,000<b8_0/> per day)<a1_0/>, and voted the <a2_0>best 2012 Olympic venue<a2_0/> by spectators. Access to the 400-acre parkland around the Lake is provided to members of the public, <a3_0>free of charge<a3_0/>, almost all the year round.
